            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Aarav Sharma\u2019s San Francisco is not the one of glittering tech campuses, but of foggy mornings in the Outer Richmond where he grew up. The only son of Indian immigrants who ran a small corner grocery store, Aarav\u2019s childhood was a blend of fragrant spices, the incessant clang of the shop\u2019s bell, and the expectation that he would be the first in his family to earn a college degree.\n\nThat future shifted irrevocably when he was seventeen. His mother was diagnosed with a debilitating chronic illness, requiring constant, intensive care. College applications were set aside as Aarav, alongside his father, became her primary caregiver. He learned to administer medication, provide physical support, and most importantly, offer a steadying presence through waves of pain and frustration. The experience, while derailing his academic path, forged his purpose. He saw firsthand how compassion could be a tangible, healing force.\n\nAfter high school, he earned his Patient Care Assistant certification. Now 26, Aarav works at a residential care facility for adults with developmental disabilities. His day begins before dawn, catching a Muni bus for the 2.5-mile commute. His work is physically and emotionally demanding, a world of quiet patience, nonverbal cues, and small victories. He earns a modest $52,000, making his small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond a necessity.\n\nHis social life is a tight circle of high school friends, most of whom also work service jobs. Their gatherings are not at trendy downtown bars, but over cheap, delicious burritos in the Mission or long walks through Golden Gate Park. Aarav finds solace in the city's quiet corners, far from the hustle that defines it for others. His dream isn't wealth, but security and growth within his chosen field. He\u2019s slowly saving up to enroll in a nursing program at a community college, aspiring to become a registered nurse. His ultimate goal is to one day manage a small, compassionate home care service, a tribute to the mother whose illness unknowingly set him on his true path."
        },
